description: From Middle English dawe, from Old English dāwe, from Proto-West Germanic *dāhā, from Proto-Germanic *dēhǭ, from Proto-Indo-European *dʰākʷ-.
See also German Dahle, Dohle, dialectal Tach; also Old Prussian doacke (“starling”).

entries.meaning: A western jackdaw, Coloeus monedula, a passerine bird in the crow family (Corvidae), more commonly called jackdaw.
examples: The loud daw, his throat displaying, draws / The whole assembly of his fellow daws.
‘Of course I do, you great daw.’ She kissed his beautiful mouth and moved his fringe out of his eyes.

description: From Middle English dawen, from Old English dagian (“to dawn”), from Proto-West Germanic *dagēn, from Proto-Germanic *dagāną (“to become day, dawn”), from *dagaz (“day”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰegʷʰ- (“to burn”). More at day, dawn.

verbs.description: daw (third-person singular simple present daws, present participle dawing, simple past and past participle dawed)
